142 - Linked List Cycle II
Problem Statement

Given the head of a linked list, return the node where the cycle begins. If there is no cycle, return null.

Approach: Floyd's Cycle Detection Algorithm

This problem is solved in two phases:

Phase 1: Detect Cycle

Use two pointers:

Slow Pointer → moves 1 step at a time.
Fast Pointer → moves 2 steps at a time.

If slow == fast, a cycle exists.

slow = slow.next;
fast = fast.next.next;
Phase 2: Find the Starting Node of the Cycle

Once a meeting point is found:

Create a new pointer start at head.
Keep slow at the meeting point.
Move both pointers one step at a time.
The node where they meet is the cycle starting node.
ListNode start = head;

while (start != slow) {
    start = start.next;
    slow = slow.next;
}

Return:

return start;
Why Does while(start != slow) Work?

After slow and fast meet inside the cycle:

Distance from head to cycle start
Distance from meeting point to cycle start

Therefore:

One pointer starts from head
One pointer starts from the meeting point

Moving both one step at a time guarantees that they will meet exactly at the cycle entry node.

